There's a replica
of Venice somewhere.
There's the Chrysler Building.


238
0:17:0,16 --> 0:17:7,28
I'm often told that my vision of a
godless future is just as devoid of
meaning as Las Vegas.


239
0:17:7,28 --> 0:17:14,8
That without God,
all you're left with is materialism
and mindless slot machines.


240
0:17:14,8 --> 0:17:19,68
But I've come here
because I think Las Vegas
reveals something fascinating,


241
0:17:19,68 --> 0:17:26,2
humanity's deep-seated belief
that we can prevail over chance.


242
0:17:26,2 --> 0:17:28,6
People come here filled with hope.


243
0:17:28,6 --> 0:17:33,44
Everybody knows the casinos
have a terrific mark-up percentage
for the house


244
0:17:33,44 --> 0:17:41,4
and yet they still go on feeding
that hope and feeding the slot
machines and losing their money.


245
0:17:41,4 --> 0:17:43,8
Hey, Richard. How's it going?


246
0:17:43,8 --> 0:17:44,12
Hey, Richard. How's it going?
OK.


247
0:17:44,12 --> 0:17:44,76
You winning?


248
0:17:44,76 --> 0:17:46,12
You winning?
No, I've lost every time so far.


249
0:17:46,12 --> 0:17:49,64
Well, now your luck's gonna change,
because I know physics!


250
0:17:49,64 --> 0:17:55,92
OK. He may look like a card sharp,
but the gentleman in the shades
is actually a physicist.


251
0:17:55,92 --> 0:18:5,56
Leonard Mlodinow is fascinated by
how human beings are incapable
of understanding chance.


252
0:18:5,56 --> 0:18:7,72
32.


253
0:18:7,72 --> 0:18:11,0
I won and I lost.


254
0:18:11,0 --> 0:18:14,64
When people are playing
these games we see around us,


255
0:18:14,64 --> 0:18:19,68
am I right that many of them,
even if there's absolutely no bias
between red and black,


256
0:18:19,68 --> 0:18:24,28
many people will say, "Oh, well it
has been red, red, red, red for such
a long time, it's black's turn."


257
0:18:24,28 --> 0:18:28,4
That's right. That's called
The Gambler's Fallacy.


258
0:18:28,4 --> 0:18:30,6
I you flip a coin a zillion times,


259
0:18:30,6 --> 0:18:34,48
you're going to get
about half a zillion heads
and half a zillion tails.


260
0:18:34,48 --> 0:18:37,8
So people's thinking goes, if they
bothered to logically think about it,


261
0:18:37,8 --> 0:18:41,76
is that,
"OK, I've seen 10 tails in a row,


262
0:18:41,76 --> 0:18:45,4
"so if it's gonna be half heads
and half tails, the heads better
catch up."


263
0:18:45,4 --> 0:18:46,44
But that's not the way it works.


264
0:18:46,44 --> 0:18:47,48
But that's not the way it works.
OK.


265
0:18:47,48 --> 0:18:52,64
You could throw it a zillion times
and get all heads.


266
0:18:52,64 --> 0:18:59,8
The point about our brain is that it
insists on seeing order, meaning and
pattern even where thereis none.


267
0:18:59,8 --> 0:19:5,4
It's a very human characteristic
to fool ourselves
that we are in control.


268
0:19:5,4 --> 0:19:8,64
In today's world,
it seems that we make more mistakes


269
0:19:8,64 --> 0:19:12,4
seeing patterns that aren't there
rather than missing patterns
that are there.


270
0:19:12,4 --> 0:19:17,64
In fact, there's a great experiment
on that, they put a rat in front of
a red light and a green light.


271
0:19:17,64 --> 0:19:21,76
And the red light and the
green light flash without any
pattern, at random.


272
0:19:21,76 --> 0:19:27,28
But the green light flashes 75% of
the time, and the red light flashes
25% of the time.


273
0:19:27,28 --> 0:19:31,28
And the rat, if it guesses
correctly which is going to flash,
it gets a little sugar water.


274
0:19:31,28 --> 0:19:33,48
So when they let the rats do this,


275
0:19:33,48 --> 0:19:38,0
they see after a while that the
green light is flashing more than
the red light


276
0:19:38,0 --> 0:19:40,56
and they just start guessing
green, green, green, green, green
every time.


277
0:19:40,56 --> 0:19:43,52
And they get it right 75% of the
time and are happy with that.


278
0:19:43,52 --> 0:19:44,96
That's what you should do.


279
0:19:44,96 --> 0:19:45,96
That's what you should do.
Yeah.


280
0:19:45,96 --> 0:19:48,6
But people, we think we know better,
right?


281
0:19:48,6 --> 0:19:53,2
So when they put humans
in front of such an experiment,


282
0:19:53,2 --> 0:19:57,12
they won't do what the rat does.
They've seen that it's 75% green
and they'll guess a pattern.


283
0:19:57,12 --> 0:19:59,68
They'll go, green, green, red,
green, green, green, red.


284
0:19:59,68 --> 0:20:3,8
They'll start spewing out
these red and greens


285
0:20:3,8 --> 0:20:7,4
in some weird pattern
that's tailored to be 75% green
and 25% red,


286
0:20:7,4 --> 0:20:12,2
thinking that they can beat the
system, just like the people here
in the casino think they can.


287
0:20:12,2 --> 0:20:16,4
And when you do that, you end up
about, I think, 60% of the time you
get it right, instead of 75%.


288
0:20:16,4 --> 0:20:18,64
And so the humans are out performed
by a rat.


289
0:20:18,64 --> 0:20:24,4
That's because we see patterns
where there aren't any. That's
just the way our minds work.


290
0:20:24,4 --> 0:20:27,72
Too clever by half. Or too clever
by three quarters, in this case.


291
0:20:27,72 --> 0:20:28,76
Too clever by half. Or too clever
by three quarters, in this case.
Yes.


292
0:20:28,76 --> 0:20:31,2
I'm going to throw everything
on my birthday.


293
0:20:31,2 --> 0:20:32,76
Yours is the 26th? Mine is the 26th!


294
0:20:32,76 --> 0:20:33,8
Yours is the 26th? Mine is the 26th!
Oh, wow!


295
0:20:33,8 --> 0:20:38,32
Both our birthdays are the 26th!
So... (LAUGHS)


296
0:20:38,32 --> 0:20:44,32
26 is even so I'm going to win
that too. Maybe I should put this
on odd?


297
0:20:44,32 --> 0:20:50,12
Perhaps this is part of the
explanation why religion evolved in
the first place,


298
0:20:50,12 --> 0:20:55,56
it satisfied our desperate desire to
find meaning and order in the chaos.


299
0:20:55,56 --> 0:21:0,72
In playing the ultimate game
of chance, Russian roulette,


300
0:21:0,72 --> 0:21:6,84
the young Graham Greene
grasped what so many of us fail to,
there is no pattern.


301
0:21:6,84 --> 0:21:8,48
26! 26!


302
0:21:8,48 --> 0:21:10,96
We have no control.


303
0:21:10,96 --> 0:21:13,52
Ooh! We came so close!


304
0:21:13,52 --> 0:21:17,96
Greene took his chances
and pulled the trigger
on another five occasions


305
0:21:17,96 --> 0:21:26,56
before the effect of what he called
"his adrenaline drug" wore off.


306
0:21:26,56 --> 0:21:32,64
What Greene did may seem crazy, but
there is a grim logic to it. Seize
the reins. Dance with death.


307
0:21:32,64 --> 0:21:35,2
You're going to die anyway.


308
0:21:35,2 --> 0:21:36,68
You're going to die anyway.
CHAMBER CLICKS


309
0:21:36,68 --> 0:21:43,16
Happily for Greene,
he beat the odds.


310
0:21:43,16 --> 0:21:46,76
Greene would later convert to
Roman Catholicism,


311
0:21:46,76 --> 0:21:49,6
but Russian roulette of a kind
stayed with him.


312
0:21:49,6 --> 0:21:57,8
As a journalist and spy,
Greene risked his life
in numerous war zones.


313
0:21:57,8 --> 0:22:0,16
"The fear of ambush served me
just as effectively


314
0:22:0,16 --> 0:22:9,8
"as the revolver from the corner
cupboard in the life-long war
against boredom."


315
0:22:9,8 --> 0:22:13,28
Tolstoy found meaning
by hiding himself away.


316
0:22:13,28 --> 0:22:16,6
Greene
went in the opposite direction.


317
0:22:16,6 --> 0:22:20,72
But the next great mind
I shall consider


318
0:22:20,72 --> 0:22:38,48
tried to argue meaning into even the
most meaningless toil imaginable.


319
0:22:38,48 --> 0:22:43,44
More and more of us now do not
believe in God or life after death.


320
0:22:43,44 --> 0:22:47,8
We live and then we die,
and that's it.


321
0:22:47,8 --> 0:22:56,6
We are born by chance and our lives
are shaped by chance events.


322
0:22:56,6 --> 0:23:0,96
I know this is a difficult pill
to swallow for many people,


323
0:23:0,96 --> 0:23:4,84
especially those for whom religion
still has a hold over their lives.


324
0:23:4,84 --> 0:23:9,64
Many people have struggled
to come to terms with the reality


325
0:23:9,64 --> 0:23:22,12
of a purely physical universe.
So, how do we find meaning?


326
0:23:22,12 --> 0:23:31,16
The Second World War laid bare the
extent of man's capacity for evil.


327
0:23:31,16 --> 0:23:36,56
In Paris, philosophers like
Albert Camus met in cafes like this


328
0:23:36,56 --> 0:23:40,44
to try to make sense
of the brutality.


329
0:23:40,44 --> 0:23:44,8
"Without the aid of eternal values,
it is legitimate


330
0:23:44,8 --> 0:23:50,8
"and necessary to wonder
whether life has a meaning."


331
0:23:50,8 --> 0:23:54,2
Camus was interested
in what he called "the absurd",


332
0:23:54,2 --> 0:23:57,4
that our life must have
meaning for us to value it,


333
0:23:57,4 --> 0:24:1,36
but we live in a world
that offers no meaning.


334
0:24:1,36 --> 0:24:5,12
Unlike Tolstoy and Graham Greene,
Camus rejected religion


335
0:24:5,12 --> 0:24:8,96
as a source of the meaning
he craved.


336
0:24:8,96 --> 0:24:11,84
He found inspiration
in another myth.


337
0:24:11,84 --> 0:24:18,32
The story of a man whom
the Ancient Greek gods had cursed.


338
0:24:18,32 --> 0:24:20,88
Camus consoled himself
with the myth of Sisyphus,


339
0:24:20,88 --> 0:24:23,8
in which Sisyphus was condemned
to spend his whole time


340
0:24:23,8 --> 0:24:27,72
rolling a boulder up a mountain and
then it rolled to the bottom again,


341
0:24:27,72 --> 0:24:29,6
he went to the bottom
and rolled it up again,


342
0:24:29,6 --> 0:24:33,84
and this went on forever.


343
0:24:33,84 --> 0:24:39,28
For Camus, accepting even this
most futile and repetitive of tasks


344
0:24:39,28 --> 0:24:42,2
and not giving up, itself had value.


345
0:24:42,2 --> 0:24:45,68
"The struggle itself towards
the heights


346
0:24:45,68 --> 0:24:48,72
"is enough to fill a man's heart.


347
0:24:48,72 --> 0:24:53,8
"We must imagine Sisyphus happy."


348
0:24:53,8 --> 0:24:54,92
Camus took comfort from this


349
0:24:54,92 --> 0:24:57,6
because by going to the bottom
of the mountain again


350
0:24:57,6 --> 0:25:2,32
and rolling the stone back up,
he was at least doing something.


351
0:25:2,32 --> 0:25:8,16
But can we really find meaning
in futile work?


352
0:25:8,16 --> 0:25:12,36
Sisyphus may seem admirable
to a French intellectual,


353
0:25:12,36 --> 0:25:15,72
but I don't see the appeal
of resigning oneself


354
0:25:15,72 --> 0:25:28,8
to life's injustices.


355
0:25:28,8 --> 0:25:31,76
India -
one of the fastest developing


356
0:25:31,76 --> 0:25:35,76
and most unequal
economies in the world.


357
0:25:35,76 --> 0:25:38,96
The human condition doesn't
come much more human than this,


358
0:25:38,96 --> 0:25:40,76
or much more extreme.


359
0:25:40,76 --> 0:25:44,72
Everything's going on -
the noise, the bustle.


360
0:25:44,72 --> 0:25:46,76
It's like an ant-heap of activity.


361
0:25:46,76 --> 0:25:56,96
It's a terrifying
and yet rather a moving sight.


362
0:25:56,96 --> 0:26:0,96
This latter-day Sisyphus
is called Hori Lal.


363
0:26:0,96 --> 0:26:3,24
His struggle is to clean the streets


364
0:26:3,24 --> 0:26:6,24
and the public lavatory
here in Varanasi.


365
0:26:6,24 --> 0:26:10,32
His task is as endless as Sisyphus'
boulder-rolling.


366
0:26:10,32 --> 0:26:14,48
These streets are never clean.


367
0:26:14,48 --> 0:26:16,4
Do you enjoy your job?


368
0:26:16,4 --> 0:26:20,4
TRANSLATION: Yes, yes.
I enjoy doing my job.


369
0:26:20,4 --> 0:26:21,72
Do you do the same thing every day?


370
0:26:21,72 --> 0:26:24,48
TRANSLATION: Yes, I do it every day.


371
0:26:24,48 --> 0:26:26,44
How long have you been
doing this job?


372
0:26:26,44 --> 0:26:30,24
TRANSLATION: It must be 20 years now.


373
0:26:30,24 --> 0:26:32,64
What hope do you have
for the future?


374
0:26:32,64 --> 0:26:34,24
TRANSLATION: What hope can I have?


375
0:26:34,24 --> 0:26:39,36
I have a job to do
and I will continue doing it.


376
0:26:39,36 --> 0:26:48,52
It's fate. What we have been made,
we will remain. It can't be changed.


377
0:26:48,52 --> 0:26:52,4
I suppose there is something
a bit inspiring about Hori Lal's


378
0:26:52,4 --> 0:26:56,24
cheerfulness and good humour
in the face of life's hardships.


379
0:26:56,24 --> 0:26:59,96
Perhaps it's what Camus saw
in the myth of Sisyphus,


380
0:26:59,96 --> 0:27:2,8
and it's certainly a wonderful
antidote to us whingers


381
0:27:2,8 --> 0:27:5,4
in the rich West,
when we dare to moan about


382
0:27:5,4 --> 0:27:14,88
patchy mobile phone reception,
or the cost of supermarket food.


383
0:27:14,88 --> 0:27:19,4
But what bothers me is why Hori Lal
has been cursed like Sisyphus.


384
0:27:19,4 --> 0:27:22,52
It's because here,
life's lottery begins at birth,


385
0:27:22,52 --> 0:27:26,4
thanks to the confines
of the ancient caste system.


386
0:27:26,4 --> 0:27:30,4
This is the Sunday edition
of the Hindustan Times


387
0:27:30,4 --> 0:27:33,44
and it's got a section called
"Matrimonials",


388
0:27:33,44 --> 0:27:39,8
in which fathers advertise
for husbands for their daughters.


389
0:27:39,8 --> 0:27:43,24
And there's a section
called "Brides",


390
0:27:43,24 --> 0:27:46,48
where men advertise for wives.


391
0:27:46,48 --> 0:27:49,8
And the men are usually described
as handsome.


392
0:27:49,8 --> 0:27:51,36
The women are often described
as homely,


393
0:27:51,36 --> 0:27:53,52
which I presume means home-loving.


394
0:27:53,52 --> 0:27:56,12
But a curious thing
about this matrimonials page


395
0:27:56,12 --> 0:27:58,36
is the way it's classified.


396
0:27:58,36 --> 0:28:1,24
There are headings like Brahmin,


397
0:28:1,24 --> 0:28:6,12
and other names from
the ancient Hindu caste system,


398
0:28:6,12 --> 0:28:12,16
whereby society is stratified
into levels, into separate castes,


399
0:28:12,16 --> 0:28:17,44
which are not supposed
to marry each other.


400
0:28:17,44 --> 0:28:20,2
Ancient Hindu scripture
divided society


401
0:28:20,2 --> 0:28:23,8
into four distinct groups
that you could be born into -


402
0:28:23,8 --> 0:28:26,6
scholars...


403
0:28:26,6 --> 0:28:28,92
warriors...


404
0:28:28,92 --> 0:28:30,56
merchants...


405
0:28:30,56 --> 0:28:33,4
and labourers.


406
0:28:33,4 --> 0:28:37,84
Falling outside this system
were the Dalits, the untouchables,


407
0:28:37,84 --> 0:28:39,8
who, like Hori Lal,


408
0:28:39,8 --> 0:28:54,2
were condemned to shovel
the excrement of the higher castes.


409
0:28:54,2 --> 0:28:57,28
This is where I think
Camus got it wrong.


410
0:28:57,28 --> 0:29:1,4
Rather than accept fate,
surely meaning is found


411
0:29:1,4 --> 0:29:7,92
when we revolt
against outrageous fortune?


412
0:29:7,92 --> 0:29:10,72
Mahendra?  Yes.
Very nice to meet you.


413
0:29:10,72 --> 0:29:16,0
Please come.  Thank you.


414
0:29:16,0 --> 0:29:18,84
TRANSLATION: When my father died,
I was told that


415
0:29:18,84 --> 0:29:20,88
because there is no money
in the family now,


416
0:29:20,88 --> 0:29:22,96
you can't study any more.


417
0:29:22,96 --> 0:29:25,52
At that time I was very sad


418
0:29:25,52 --> 0:29:33,32
because I had this dream
from the start, I have to study.


419
0:29:33,32 --> 0:29:37,8
Like Hori Lal, Mahendra is a Dalit.


420
0:29:37,8 --> 0:29:42,52
His father died when he was 14 years
old, leaving the family penniless.


421
0:29:42,52 --> 0:29:45,44
Mahendra spent the next four years
working as a bonded labourer,


422
0:29:45,44 --> 0:29:47,6
weaving saris.


423
0:29:47,6 --> 0:29:51,92
But, unlike Sisyphus,
Mahendra defied the gods


424
0:29:51,92 --> 0:29:54,76
and threw his boulder away.


425
0:29:54,76 --> 0:29:58,84
TRANSLATION: I had to face so much
discrimination in the society


426
0:29:58,84 --> 0:30:2,48
for being a Dalit that I felt
education could be a good medium


427
0:30:2,48 --> 0:30:5,68
to get out of the system.


428
0:30:5,68 --> 0:30:9,6
A lot of people in your position
would probably have given up.


429
0:30:9,6 --> 0:30:15,16
I hugely admire you for not giving
up, but what drove you at that time?


430
0:30:15,16 --> 0:30:19,6
TRANSLATION: I had always felt
that I have to become


431
0:30:19,6 --> 0:30:23,92
a part of the mainstream society.


432
0:30:23,92 --> 0:30:28,56
And that is why I have this thing
that I have to study a lot


433
0:30:28,56 --> 0:30:36,68
and earn money so that
I can reach mainstream society.


434
0:30:36,68 --> 0:30:39,12
Today, Mahendra is studying
for a master's degree


435
0:30:39,12 --> 0:30:41,84
and wants to fight the Dalit cause -


436
0:30:41,84 --> 0:30:47,44
help other boulder-rollers break
free from their struggle.


437
0:30:47,44 --> 0:30:50,72
It is wonderful to see how
an individual can bring himself


438
0:30:50,72 --> 0:30:57,32
out of poverty and downtrodden-ness.


439
0:30:57,32 --> 0:30:59,84
With Mahendra,
we come closer to finding


440
0:30:59,84 --> 0:31:2,4
at least one worthwhile
meaning of life.


441
0:31:2,4 --> 0:31:4,72
He is creating his own meaning,


442
0:31:4,72 --> 0:31:10,84
but it has a deeper purpose, making
a difference to others as well.


443
0:31:10,84 --> 0:31:13,36
We can find meaning in struggle,


444
0:31:13,36 --> 0:31:16,96
but we have to define
our own meaning in our own struggle,


445
0:31:16,96 --> 0:31:34,64
not one dictated by the gods, by
authority or by accident of birth.


446
0:31:34,64 --> 0:31:37,6
So I think meaning is subjective,


447
0:31:37,6 --> 0:31:40,28
something personal
we may not all agree on.


448
0:31:40,28 --> 0:31:47,36
But that shouldn't be an invitation
to egotism or self-absorption.


449
0:31:47,36 --> 0:31:52,56
Here in northern India,
Westerners still come in droves


450
0:31:52,56 --> 0:32:1,8
in the hope of finding some deeper
meaning in Eastern mysticism.


451
0:32:1,8 --> 0:32:3,24
People go up mountains
for refreshment,


452
0:32:3,24 --> 0:32:5,8
they go up mountains for wisdom.


453
0:32:5,8 --> 0:32:8,56
Moses went up Mount Sinai
and came down


454
0:32:8,56 --> 0:32:11,76
with the tablets
of traditional Hebrew wisdom.


455
0:32:11,76 --> 0:32:14,8
There are lots of people
who come from all over the world


456
0:32:14,8 --> 0:32:17,68
to a place like this,
up a mountain like this,


457
0:32:17,68 --> 0:32:19,56
where there's a Tibetan monastery,


458
0:32:19,56 --> 0:32:26,88
seeking what they would call
spiritual wisdom.


459
0:32:26,88 --> 0:32:31,32
Geshe Lhakdor
is a Master of Tibetan Buddhism.


460
0:32:31,32 --> 0:32:36,48
He's the Dalai Lama's
official translator and archivist.


461
0:32:36,48 --> 0:32:40,44
The complete teaching
of the Buddha is aimed towards


462
0:32:40,44 --> 0:32:43,36
transforming your mental outlook


463
0:32:43,36 --> 0:32:47,48
because the ultimate purpose
is to remove all kinds of problems


